    <h1>About</h1>

    <p>Hi, I'm Rustam.</p>

    <p>I'm a solo founder and AI engineer. I build products with AI agents — tools designed for people who value simplicity, privacy, and speed.</p>

    <h2>What I'm Building</h2>

    <p><a href="https://superduperai.co">SuperDuperAI</a> is a product studio, not a single product.</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Video Editor</strong> — AI-powered video creation platform. Turn vibes into videos instantly. Multi-agent AI system for professional video creation without skills, equipment, or budget.</li>
      <li><strong>Super Chatbot</strong> — Multi-agent chatbot platform with RAG, tool use, and custom knowledge bases. Deploy on web, Telegram, or WhatsApp.</li>
      <li><strong>FaceAlarm</strong> — Face yoga tracker with daily selfie alarm. AI-powered alarm won't turn off until you take a selfie.</li>
      <li><strong>Jaw Harp Synth</strong> — Digital kubyz (jaw harp) synthesizer for iOS. Traditional instrument sounds with modern digital effects.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Each one started as a simple hypothesis, was validated fast, and follows the same principles: AI-first, privacy-respecting, minimal, useful. Everything I build is open source or shared on <a href={SITE.social.github}>GitHub</a>.</p>

    <h2>Unlock Manifesto</h2>

    <p><em>Not where everyone is — where I'm the only one.</em></p>

    <p>I started Life2Film in 2014 — tools to turn everyday moments into stories. The technology wasn't ready. I closed it in 2021. The dream never left. SuperDuperAI is the second chapter of the same story.</p>

    <p>Building products is how I think. Each one is an experiment — a question asked to the world. Creativity is freedom. AI and agents don't replace human creativity — they remove the friction so we can focus on what matters: ideas, craft, time with people we love. We should be creators, not robots.</p>

    <h3>Principles</h3>

    <p>Technology, ecology, and humanity should complement each other. The tools we build should make life better without making the world worse.</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>AI is the foundation, not a feature.</strong> Every product starts with what AI can do better than manual work.</li>
      <li><strong>Offline-first when possible.</strong> Independence from connectivity. Independence from servers. Your tool should work on a plane, in a village, during an outage.</li>
      <li><strong>Data is power — it belongs to people.</strong> Privacy isn't a feature, it's architecture. On-device processing, local storage, no accounts when possible. If I can't see your data, I can't leak it, sell it, or be forced to hand it over.</li>
      <li><strong>Open source by default.</strong> Knowledge compounds when it's shared.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>What I want to unlock</h3>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>Memory tools</strong> — ways to capture, store, and relive life. I've been thinking about this since 2014. Technology finally caught up.</li>
      <li><strong>Tools I'd use myself</strong> — I build what I need first. If it helps others — great.</li>
      <li><strong>A community of builders</strong> — people who ship fast, respect users, and play long-term games.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Strategy</h3>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>One pain, one feature, launch.</strong> Not platforms. Not roadmaps. One problem, one solution, shipped in days. If nobody wants it — kill it and move on.</li>
      <li><strong>Speed over perfection.</strong> Ship, learn, iterate. The market teaches faster than planning.</li>
      <li><strong>Fair pricing.</strong> Free if it costs me nothing, honest pricing if it does. No lock-in, no dark patterns.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Antifragile architecture</h3>

    <p>Modular — any piece replaceable. No single point of failure. Small bets with asymmetric upside: limited downside, unlimited potential.</p>

    <h3>The oath</h3>

    <p>I choose the silence of future trends, not the noise of today's crowd. I build systems that grow stronger from impact. I earn before I automate. I cut everything except value. I measure reality, not expectations. I keep the right to change my mind — fast.</p>

    <p>We should be creators, not robots. Technology should free humans to create, to reflect, to live — not turn them into data sources or engagement metrics.</p>

    <p>The world is one. Borders are lines on maps. Problems are shared. Solutions should be too.</p>

    <p><em>evidence-first · wip=1 · ship > perfect</em></p>

